          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Whole Lion's Mane powder</td><td>~2 to 5%</td><td>20 to 50 mg</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Typical Lion's Mane extract</td><td>~10%</td><td>100 mg</td></tr>
            <tr><td>High-end commercial extract</td><td>~30%</td><td>300 mg</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-highlight"><td><strong>DayShift extract</strong></td><td><strong>≥70%</strong></td><td><strong>≥700 mg</strong></td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>What This Means For DayShift's 300 mg</h3>
        <p>DayShift uses 300 mg of a Lion's Mane extract standardized to ≥70% β-glucans, USDA Organic, and FDA-notified GRAS. That delivers ≥210 mg of β-glucans per serving, the β-glucan content equivalent of approximately 2,000 mg of typical Lion's Mane extract (assuming ~10% β-glucan content, the low end of the standard industry range).</p>
        <p>300 mg of a properly standardized extract delivers more measurable Lion's Mane actives than 2,000 mg of an unstandardized product. Concentration, not gross weight, is the measure that holds up under a lab test.</p>

        <h3>Why This Is Honest, Not Marketing</h3>
        <p>β-glucan content is verifiable. You can confirm it with the Certificate of Analysis on the ingredient. "Mg of mushroom" alone tells you nothing about how concentrated the actives are. We chose the metric that can be measured and reported, not the one that just looks big on a label.</p>
